{[%evp 0,16,28,23,14,-1,-1,4,4,-4,23,-11,17,17,17,17,34,14,18]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 {[#] In the second installment of 'Repertoire for Black
against 1.d4', I suggest an opening repertoire against 3.Nf3 based on the
Ragozin defense (4...Bb4) and Modern queen's gambit (4...a6). Similarly to the
Repertoire against the Catalan, the idea is to have one equalizing opening
system that you would be comfortable playing against strong opponents, as well
as one sharp system that you would use to imbalance the game, get your
opponent out of his comfort zone, or just get a playable game without much
opening theory, hoping to outplay him in the long run. In this database,
Ragozin defense will have a role of a solid equalizing weapon, while the
Modern queen's gambit will be the sharp one.} ({In addition to the main line 4.
Nc3, White has several sidelines. The most popular one is:} 4. Bg5 {when we
can continue in the Ragozin spirit with} Bb4+ {and White's only independent
try (since 5.Nc3 transposes to the main repertoire) is} 5. Nbd2 {Black should
accept the gambit:} dxc4 {and the game becomes quite sharp early on. Black has
good chances in the arising positions, as you can discover in Chapter 14.}) ({
The other, more positional alternative is:} 4. e3 {when I suggest that we
continue in Queen's Indian spirit with:} b6 {This way, Black keeps a flexible
pawn structure with all pieces on the board. This opening system is covered in
Chapter 15.}) 4... Bb4 {Ragozin defense is one of the most popular defenses
against White's classical setup with Nf3 and Nc3 on grandmaster level. I can
not think of many top contemporary players who have not, at least, given it a
try with Black pieces, while some of them, like Magnus Carlsen and Wesley So,
keep it as a part of their regular repertoire. Compared to the Queen's Gambit
with 4...Be7, the Ragozin gives Black more opportunities for active play,
while still keeping a reserve of solidity and I think that it can be played
successfully on all levels. In addition to opening files divided into 13
chapters, in this opening database I also provide a breakdown of typical pawn
structures for this opening repertoire. I think that it is very important to
be aware of typical features of most common pawn structures and understand
their transformations because a lot of strategic fight in the Ragozin and
Queen's gambit revolves exactly around getting into a favorable pawn structure.
} ({The basis for our sharp repertoire is the modern approach to the Queen's
gambit with} 4... a6 $5 {[#] Now, this is not exactly a sharp variation in the
strict sense of the word. Here we are talking about an opening that is still
relatively unexplored and offers chances for a balanced fight without the
chains of deep opening theory. The move itself is not pointless - Black simply
prepares to capture on c4 and protect the pawn with ..b7-b5, similarly to the
Slav defense. However, the omission of c6-move gives Black some extra options,
which are explained in this database.  I have used this system occasionally
and I think that it can work very well against 1. lower-rated opponents; 2.
young players who are inexperienced in maneuvering battles; and 3. players who
do not like to play or have insufficient understanding of the Carlsbad pawn
structure.  I have noticed a similar pattern in games of many other strong
players, as well, so I think that this can be a good way to just get a game
and try to outplay your opponent based on superior knowledge and/or
understanding.} {White's main response to the 'Modern Queen's gambit declined'
is} 5. cxd5 ({It is very important that the direct} 5. Bg5 {[#] is well met by}
dxc4 6. e4 ({Other options, also covered in this chapter, are:} 6. a4 Nc6 $1 7.
e3 Na5) ({and} 6. e3 b5 7. a4 c6 $1 8. axb5 cxb5 9. Nxb5 axb5 10. Rxa8 Bb7 11.
Ra1 Bb4+) 6... b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 hxg5 10. Bxg5 Nbd7 {[#] when we
get a position very similar to the main line of the Botvinnik system of the Slav
defense. However, compared to that position, Black has a big improvement here
- his light-squared bishop is open and it will exert a strong pressure along
the h1-a8 diagonal. In Chapter 10, you can see that it is actually White, not
Black, that has to play more precisely here to hold the balance!}) ({White
also has two rather positional responses to 4...a6:} 5. e3 {[#] when I
recommend the most complex approach with} b6 $5) ({and} 5. c5 {[#] when Black
can play principally with} b6 ({or more risky with} 5... Nc6 $5 6. Bf4 g6) 6.
cxb6 cxb6 {Both variations are analyzed in Chapter 11.}) ({Some rare
alternatives, such as} 5. g3 dxc4 6. Bg2 b5 7. a4 b4 8. Ne5 Ra7 {[#] are
analyzed together with 5.Bg5 in Chapter 10.}) 5... exd5 {[#] What has Black
achieved with a6-move, compared to the regular QGD lines? I would say, four
things: 1. he has avoided the Nge2, f3 variation; 2. he has reserved the
option of developing his bishop to d6, rather than e7; 3. he has obtained
extra ways to protect the b7-pawn (with Ra7, b7-b5, or just sacrifice it!); 4.
he has avoided well-known opening theory. This is not so bad for a new opening
system!} 6. Bg5 {This is the standard bishop's development in the Queen's
gambit.} ({Alternatives} 6. Bf4) (6. Qb3 $5) ({and} 6. g3 {are all covered in
detail in Chapter 12.}) 6... Be6 $5 {[#] This is the point of Black's setup.
He does not have to defend the pawn with c7-c6, but rather develops his bishop
and plans to continue Nbd7 and Bd6. It is a more active setup compared to the
classical QGD and White has to solve some novel strategic problems. This often
proves a difficult task for inexperienced or weaker players and they tend to
choose a wrong plan, piece exchange, or a pawn structure at some point. White
has several possibilities here, but the main line goes:} 7. e3 Nbd7 8. Bd3 Bd6
{and in Chapter 13, we will look at a great number of examples to get a good
feel for the position and the typical plans for both sides.}) {White has many
ways to tackle the Ragozin. The most popular one is} 5. Bg5 ({Almost equally
as popular is} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 {when the exchange on d5 has some pros and
cons for both sides, compared to 5.Bg5.} ({As is often customary in the
Ragozin, White can give a queen check:} 6. Qa4+ {[#] forcing blackBlack knight to}
Nc6 {when it is much more difficult for Black to achieve counterplay in the
center with ...c7-c5 break. After} 7. Bg5 h6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. e3 O-O {we reach
a position where a lot of maneuvering usually takes place, as in the exchange
variation of the Queen's gambit. This is the topic of Chapter 5.}) ({It should
also be added that a historically rare, but lately increasingly popular
alternative} 6. Bf4 {is covered in Chapter 5, as well.}) 6... h6 7. Bh4 {
[#] This bishop retreat, covered in Chapter 7, is White's main premise in the
5.cxd5 variation, since the c4-pawn is not hanging anymore. He would like to
keep the pin on the knight for as long as possible and thereby hinder Black's
ideal development or force him to weaken his king's position with ...g7-g5.} ({
In Chapter 6, we look at the alternative} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 {[#] which, however, is
not as principled for White here as it is in 5.Bg5 variation. The reason is
that black light-squared bishop has an open diagonal h3-c8 now, making it more
easy for him to equalize the game. White has several possibilities:} 8. Qb3 (8.
Rc1) ({and} 8. e3)) 7... O-O $5 {[#] This move has not become popular until
recently. 7...Nbd7, 7...c5 and 7...g5 were all tried at this point, but in the
last couple of years, 7...0-0 in connection with Black's next move has
established itself as a very reliable choice against White's setup.} 8. e3 Bf5
{The main justification for such bold bishop development is that after} 9. Qb3
Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Nbd7 $1 11. Qxb7 c5 {[#] Black obtains sufficient compensation
for the pawn. White has many different attempts to play for advantage along
the way, but Black seems to be holding his own in all variations, so this
looks like a really good equalizing weapon for Black.}) ({Another popular
approach to the Ragozin is} 5. Qa4+ {[#] provoking} Nc6 {In Chapter 8 we
analyze White's different attempts to use the position of the knight on c6 to
his advantage. After} 6. e3 ({Sidelines are} 6. Ne5 Bd7 7. Nxd7) ({and} 6. a3
Bxc3+ 7. bxc3) 6... O-O {White's two main continuations are} 7. Bd2 ({and} 7.
Qc2 {However, Black is in time with central counterplay - either with dxc4,
Bd6, e5 plan or Re8, e5 one.})) ({The last White's answer leading to a pure
Ragozin type of position is} 5. Qb3 {[#] covered in Chapter 9, when after} c5
6. dxc5 {I would give preference to} Na6 $5 ({over the more common} 6... Nc6))
({Of course, White has a host of other opening choices against the Ragozin,
though most of them are not in the scope of this opening database since they
transpose into different branches of the Nimzo-Indian defense. They will,
therefore, be covered in the third installment of the opening repertoire for
Black against 1.d4. The most common one in this group is} 5. e3 {[#]} O-O 6.
Bd3 {transposing directly into the main line of the 4.e3 Nimzo-Indian.}) (5.
Bd2 {[#] has become a very popular option for White in recent years, but
we shall rather analyze it in a chapter on 4.Bd2 Nimzo-Indian.} O-O 6. e3) (5.
a3 {is sometimes played, as well, and it is most likely to transpose to an a3
branch of the 4.e4 Nimzo after:} Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. e3 O-O {[#]}) ({Another
interesting approach is} 5. g3 {[#] leading to a Nimzo-Catalan hybrid.
Actually, after} O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4 7. O-O Nc6 {we get the main line of 4.g3
Nimzo-Indian that will also be covered in the next installment.}) ({Finally,} 
5. Qc2 {[#] is a fairly rare continuation, but as it transposes directly into
4.Qc2 d5 5.Nf3 line of the Nimzo-Indian, we will cover it in that chapter.})
5... h6 {[#] This is my main suggestion because it gives Black the best
chances to equalize the game.} ({However, in Chapter 4, I also offer an
alternative:} 5... dxc4 6. e4 h6 $5 {[#]} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 {which can lead to a
more double-edge type of position after} 8. Bxc4 c5 9. e5 Qd8 10. O-O O-O {
[#] Black is very solid here, while White usually tries to attack on the
kingside. This can be a good option to surprise your opponent or just get a
different kind of position compared to the regular Ragozin, with mutual
chances.}) 6. Bxf6 {With the exchange on f6, White hopes to increase his
pressure on the d5-pawn and force Black to make concessions in the center.} ({
In Chapter 1, we cover a less principled and rare continuation} 6. Bh4 {[#]}
dxc4 ({including the alternative} 6... g5 $5 7. Bg3 Ne4)) 6... Qxf6 7. e3 {
[#] This is the main line of this variation. White just wants to develop
quickly and use his slight lead in development to obtain initiative in the
middlegame.} ({The main alternative,} 7. Qa4+ {[#] is in focus in Chapter 1.
After} Nc6 8. e3 O-O {White has two attempts to play for advantage:} 9. Be2 ({
and} 9. Rc1 {Black has to play precisely, but I think that he can ultimately
equalize.})) ({In Chapter 2, we cover a positional alternative} 7. Qb3 c5 8.
cxd5 exd5 {[#] where White usually plays for a middlegame with} 9. a3 ({
although some players prefer a riskless endgame after} 9. dxc5 Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3
Qxc3+ 11. bxc3) 9... Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3) 7... O-O 8. Rc1 {This is the key
variation in this system and I suggest a less known move} Nc6 $5 {[#]} ({
instead of the main line} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 c5 {However, 8...Nc6 has been
gaining a lot of popularity lately. Black would like to equalize by breaking
in the center with ...e6-e5. This allows him to free up his pieces. I have
analyzed 6 different white responses to 8...Nc6 and I did not find any
problems for Black if he plays precisely. So, it can surely be a good
alternative to the heavily analyzed main line that starts with 8...dxc4.}) *

