1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bg5 {[#] This is the most natural
way to develop for White. The difference compared to 5.cxd5 exd5 6.Bg5 is that
White would like to remain more flexible in terms of the central pawn
structure. This also means that he has to be prepared for transposition into
various branches of the Vienna variation after 5...dxc4. Another important
strategic point of omitting the exchange on d5 is that White does not open up
the h3-c8 diagonal for Black's light-squared bishop. Black's solid reply to 5.
Bg5 is} h6 6. Bxf6 {This is by far White's most common treatment of this
position. The exchange on f6 gives him an important opening tempo and
increases the pressure against d5-pawn in many lines. Black, in return, gets
long-term consolation in form of the bishop pair.} ({A much more rare
alternative is} 6. Bh4 {because this allows Black to win the c4-pawn. You will
see this move more often in shorter time controls because it allows White to
play for an initiative in imbalanced positions that usually arise after} dxc4 ({
Black can also play for a different, more of a Nimzo-Indian type of position
with} 6... g5 $5 {[#] This was a choice of super-GMs Mamedyarov and Yu Yangyi,
so it deserves our attention. After} 7. Bg3 Ne4 8. Qc2 h5 {White needs to move
his h-pawn to save the bishop:} 9. h3 (9. h4 {as played in Lalith,B (2527)
-Neelash, S (2373) Chittagong BAN 2018, 1-0 (33), can be met simply with} g4 10.
Ne5 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Nxg3 12. fxg3 Nd7 $11) 9... Nc6 {Among several alternatives,
this is the best developing move - also putting pressure on the d4-pawn. There
is no need to rush the exchange on g3.} 10. e3 ({White has no time to preserve
the bishop from exchange} 10. Bh2 {due to} g4 11. cxd5 exd5 12. hxg4 hxg4 13.
Bxc7 {and here Black has a pretty cool queen sacrifice:} Rxh1 $1 14. Bxd8 Bf5
15. Nd2 Rxd8 $36) 10... Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Nxg3 12. fxg3 Qd6 {[#] This position
was reached in the top-level game ½-½ (16) Grischuk, A (2767)-Mamedyarov, S 
(2809) Berlin GER 2018. Grischuk played it safe and forced a three-fold
repetition, although sharper alternatives exist.} 13. Kf2 (13. Qf2 {was seen
in the aforementioned game and the position was repeated three times like
this:} Qa3 14. Qc2 Qd6 $11) ({White can also complete his development quickly
with a pawn sacrifice:} 13. O-O-O Qxg3 {He might obtain some compensation, but
Black is very solid. For example:} 14. cxd5 exd5 15. e4 Be6 16. exd5 Bxd5 17.
Re1+ Kf8 $15) 13... h4 14. g4 Bd7 {Just completing development and remaining
flexible with the king. The g5-pawn is not really hanging because of Qg3-xe3.
In one correspondence game, White chose a bit unnatural:} 15. Kg1 ({I
investigated a more human-like continuation:} 15. cxd5 exd5 16. e4 {and found
that Black is doing well after the pawn sacrifice:} f6 $1 17. exd5 Ne7 18. c4
c6 $1 $132 {and if the position opens up, white king begins to feel unsafe:}
19. dxc6 (19. Re1 cxd5 20. c5 Qg3+ 21. Kg1 Kd8 $13) 19... Bxc6 20. Be2 (20. d5
Qc5+ $19) 20... Bxf3 21. Bxf3 Qxd4+ 22. Ke2 Qe5+ 23. Kf2 $11) 15... Rg8 16. Rb1
b6 {The position is complex, but I don't see any issues for Black.} 17. e4 (17.
cxd5 exd5 18. e4 dxe4 19. Qxe4+ Kf8 $13) 17... dxe4 18. Qxe4 f6 19. Rd1 Rg7 20.
Nd2 Kf7 $13 21. Qf3 Rf8 22. c5 Qe7 23. Nb3 a5 24. Kh2 Kg8 25. Bb5 {1/2-1/2 (25)
Valak,A (2339)-Adams,J (2329) ICCF email 2016}) {At this point, White has
several options. The one that makes the most sense to me is} 7. Qa4+ ({Clearly,
} 7. e4 $2 {does not work now because of} g5 8. Bg3 Nxe4) ({The most common
move in the position is a somewhat lazy} 7. e3 b5 8. a4 c6 {[#] White hopes to
