1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. Qb3 {[#] The
main focus of this chapter is on this queen move. Similarly to 7.Qa4+, White
quickly attacks the b4-bishop. The difference is that here, the idea is to
recapture on c3 with the queen, keeping a simple pawn structure. This is one
of the most positional variations against the Ragozin defense and is usually
chosen by white players who like simple positions with very little risk.
Consequently, the drawing margin here is pretty big and Black should not have
many problems out of the opening if he knows what he is doing.} ({We will also
mention two rare 7th move alternatives: 1)} 7. Rc1 {White prepares to
recapture on c3 with a rook. However, here Black can use the Ragozin-pin to
his advantage:} dxc4 {and now every attempt to recoup the pawn will be
answered by 8...b5. White's most common reply is, therefore:} 8. Qa4+ ({
White can also try to play for the Catalan-type compensation with} 8. g3 b5 9.
Bg2 Bb7 10. O-O Bxc3 11. Rxc3 O-O 12. b3 {and here Black has an excellent way
to 'normalize' the pawn structure by giving back the extra pawn:} c5 $1 13.
bxc4 b4 14. Rd3 a5 $15 {and Black has better long-term chances due to his
queenside majority, as in Polak, T (2543)-Swiercz, D (2585) Czechia 2011, 0-1 
(66)}) 8... Nc6 9. a3 ({White fell for a nice trick in the following game:} 9.
Ne5 $2 Bd7 10. Nxd7 Qxd4 $1 {The knight on d7 has nowhere to retreat.} 11. Rd1
Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qxc3+ {and he resigned in Prie,E (2491)-Palac,M (2583) Cap
d'Agde 2008, 0-1 (12), not waiting for} 13. Rd2 O-O-O $19) 9... Bxc3+ 10. Rxc3
{White has invariably recaptured with the rook here, probably to justify 7.
Rc1.} ({Objectively speaking, though, somewhat better is} 10. bxc3 {and now
after the precise} Qe7 $1 11. Ra1 Bd7 12. Qxc4 O-O 13. e3 Rac8 $11 {we get a
structure similar to the one we have seen in Chapter 1, only with a few extra
tempi for Black. He obtains a comfortable game with the standard ...b7-b6, ...
Nc6-a5 and ...c7-c5.}) 10... Qf5 $1 $15 {[#] This strong move highlights the
defects of the White's setup. 11...Qb1 is a threat, as well as 11...b5, so
Black gets to keep his extra pawn.} 11. Qd1 ({The other possibility is} 11.
Qxc4 Qb1+ 12. Rc1 Qxb2 $15 {but this is also just an extra pawn for Black.
White failed to prove any compensation in the following encounter:} 13. Qc3
Qxc3+ 14. Rxc3 Bd7 15. g3 O-O-O 16. Bg2 Rhe8 17. O-O e5 18. d5 Nd4 $17 {
1/2-1/2 (44) Kustar, S (2351)-Farago, I (2507) Budapest 2004}) 11... b5 12. g3
Bb7 13. Bg2 {and here in the game Sofrevski, J (2415)-Mitkov, N (2370) Skopje
1991, ½-½ (38), Black missed a really strong and somewhat unexpected
resource:} O-O-O $1 14. O-O e5 $17 {and Black has a great position.}) ({and 2)
} 7. g3 O-O 8. Bg2 dxc4 9. O-O Nc6 {which actually transposes into a variation
of 4.g3 Nimzo-Indian that we will cover in the third and final installment of
1.d4 Repertoire for Black.}) 7... c5 {This standard move is possible now,
compared to 7.Qa4+. Black protects the bishop and fights for the center at the
same time.} 8. cxd5 {The strategic plot of 7.Qb3+ setup is to play against the
isolated d5-pawn, so from White's perspective this exchange should happen
sooner, rather than later. Other moves are possible as well, but White does
not need to allow Black a possibility to capture on c4.} exd5 {[#] At this
point, White has two main directions. The first one is to force the exchange
on c3 and play the middlegame against the hanging pawns on d5 and c5 (pawn
structure #10). The second one is to take on c5 and play the pawn structure #2.
} 9. a3 {The first approach gives White more strategic flexibility,} ({
compared to} 9. dxc5 {when the pawn structure and appropriate plans are more
or less fixed and straightforward. After} Bxc3+ {White usually goes for the
endgame with} 10. Qxc3 ({although} 10. bxc3 {is playable, as well. Now after}
O-O 11. Nd4 {White plants his knight on the dominant d4-square and threatens
to win the second pawn - the one on d5. The issue with this is that he has
seriously neglected his development, so Black should not waste any time. The
right move is:} Be6 $1 12. Qxb7 {Materialistic approach is principled, but
also risky.} ({White can also play it safe with} 12. e3 Nd7 13. Qa3 Rfc8 $11 {
but Black gets his pawn back, with a good position. The d5-pawn is no worse
than the one on c3.} 14. c6 $5 {White changes the pawn structure in order
to close down the c-file.} (14. Be2 Nxc5 15. O-O Ne4 16. Rac1 b6 $11 {1/2-1/2 
(29) Yermolinsky, A (2588)-Serper, G (2540) Salt Lake City 1999}) 14... bxc6 15.
Ba6 Rc7 {Black is doing okay here. There is no more pressure against the
c3-pawn, but in return, he got the opportunity to chase away white knight with
...c6-c5 at the right moment.} 16. O-O (16. Qd6 Qe5 17. Qxe5 Nxe5 18. O-O c5
19. Nxe6 fxe6 $15 {0-1 (31) Horvath,G (2420)-Tolk,P (2300) Cattolica 1992})
16... Rb8 $11 {0-1 (43) Visakh,N (2303)-Kozusek,D (2090) Al Ain 2013}) 12...
Nd7 {[#] For two sacrificed pawns, Black gets a serious lead in development.
Besides, these two extra pawns are more of weaklings than strengths for White.
He has several ways to try to keep his material advantage.} 13. c6 {This one
is the riskiest and also the most testing for Black. The c6-pawn will be
difficult to recoup, but on the other hand, White seriously falls behind in
development.} ({Alternatives are} 13. g3 Rfb8 14. Qc7 {This was seen in the
game Wang, S (2267)-Xu, Y (2446) Qinhuangdao 2017, ½-½ (35),} ({In case of} 14.
Qa6 Nxc5 15. Qa3 {black gets a flurry o tactical activity based on the Nc5-d3+
motif.} Qe7 $1 16. Qc1 Bh3 $1 17. Qd1 Bxf1 18. Kxf1 Rb2 $36 {with palpable
pressure as White struggles to complete his development.}) {and here I suggest
a small improvement:} 14... Qg6 $5 $146 {threatening the unpleasant 15...Rb1+.
After} 15. f3 Rc8 16. Qf4 {Black can choose from two ways to equalize return
the pawn and obtain material equality:} Nxc5 ({or} 16... Rxc5 17. Rc1 Rac8 $11)
17. Bg2 Bd7 18. O-O Na4 $11) ({and} 13. e3 Nxc5 14. Qb2 {when Black's
compensation for the pawn was obvious in Nikolic, P (2652)-Kacheishvili, G (2570)
Ohrid 2001, ½-½ (19), although the most interesting seems to be} Bf5 $5 $146
{[#] once again, taking control of the important b1-h7 diagonal. Since White
probably does not want to trade the powerful d4-knight for the bishop and
other moves are too slow, he might play:} 15. Be2 {when both} Nd3+ ({and} 15...
Rab8 16. Qd2 Ne4 17. Qc1 Rfc8 18. O-O Nxc3 $11) 16. Bxd3 Bxd3 17. f3 Rfe8 18.
Kf2 Qh4+ 19. g3 Qh3 $44 {promise Black to achieve the balance through active
play.}) 13... Rab8 $5 {Hou Yifan sacrifices the third pawn (!), just to open
more attacking avenues toward the White king.} ({Black could have done even
without that sacrifice:} 13... Rfb8 14. Qc7 Ne5 $36) 14. Qxa7 Ra8 15. Qc7 Ne5
$36 {White picked up the whole queenside with his queen, but his development
suffered greatly and now he has to play very precisely to defend against
Black's threats.} 16. e3 ({One of the nice lines is} 16. Qd6 Qf4 $1 17. Qb4
Rxa2 $1 $36 {showing why the sacrifice on a7 was useful for Black.}) 16... Rfc8
17. Qb6 $2 {White has two possible squares to retreat and he chooses the wrong
one.} ({It was necessary to continue} 17. Qd6 {even though Hou Yifan had
surely prepared} Rxc6 $3 {[#]} 18. Qb4 $8 {The only move.} ({The point is in
the following discovered attack:} 18. Nxc6 Ng4 19. Ne7+ Kh8 $19 {and White
king falls under irresistible attack.}) 18... Ng4 19. Qb2 Rxc3 $1 20. Bb5 $8
Rb3 $3 {[#] The stunner! Rook steps on a square that is attacked three times.
Yet, such brilliancy leads only to a drawish endgame after:} 21. axb3 Qxf2+ $1
22. Qxf2 Rxa1+ 23. Kd2 Ra2+ 24. Nc2 Nxf2 25. Ra1 Ne4+ 26. Kc1 Rxa1+ 27. Nxa1
$11) 17... Rcb8 18. Qc5 Rb2 $40 {Black's attack is too strong now.} 19. f4 Rxg2
$1 20. O-O-O Rgxa2 $19 {0-1 (25) Zhou,W (2585)-Hou,Y (2589) Xinghua 2010})
10... Qxc3+ 11. bxc3 {[#] This is the low risk-low reward endgame that some
players prefer with White. Black has several attempts to equalize and, in my
view, the most reliable one is:} Na6 {Black just tries to recoup the c5-pawn
as quickly as possible.} ({Other possibilities are:} 11... O-O 12. e3 Be6 (12...
Nd7 13. Rd1 Nxc5 (13... Nf6 $5) 14. Rxd5 b6) 13. Nd4 Rc8 14. Bb5 Rxc5 15. Kd2)
{White has a wide variety of options here:} 12. Rd1 {This is the most direct
one.} (12. Nd4 {This (or 12.e3 first, followed by 13.Nd4) is the most common
