this position: 1) keep the central tension and 2) close down the center and
transpose into pawn structure #4. The first plan can be accomplished with two
moves: 10...b6 and 10...Nd7. Both lead to sound, solid positions, though I
would prefer the former one. The second plan is accomplished with 10...c4,
although this looks a bit premature as White can undermine it immediately with
11.b3. However, things are not that simple there, as we will see.} b6 {This is
the most solid approach and the best move order to achieve pawn structure #10.}
({The sharper alternative is} 10... c4 $5 {[#] which came into the limelight
