1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5 exd5 {[#] In this part of the
opening course (Chapters 5-7) we deal with positions that arise after the
quick exchange on d5. This simplifies central play a bit and helps Black solve
some of his opening problems with the light-squared bishop. On the other hand,
White gets the possibility to preserve his dark-squared bishop by retreating
it to h4 after being attacked by ...h7-h6. This is not really an option in
case of 5.Bg5, as we have seen in previous chapters. In this chapter, we focus
on a positional alternative:} 6. Qa4+ ({We will also look at a rare, although
increasingly popular move} 6. Bf4 {Compared to g5, this is a slightly inferior
square to develop the bishop, but it is nevertheless better than sitting at
home. Here, among several possibilities I can recommend two: a solid one and a
sharp one - depending on your preferences.} {The solid continuation is} c6 {
when Black is ready to play a sort of a Queen's gambit with pawn structure #7.
His plan is to develop the bishop to f5 and maybe exchange a pair of pieces,
when his position would be completely fine.} ({Probably a more principled, but
also much sharper continuation is:} 6... Ne4 7. Rc1 ({Svidler included a check:
} 7. Qa4+ Nc6 8. Rc1 O-O {but this was probably not necessary. His follow up
was a bit careless, as well:} 9. g3 $6 (9. h3 {was safer}) {and Mamedyarov did
not miss the chance to obtain the initiative with:} 9... g5 $1 10. Be3 f5 $36
11. Bg2 f4 12. gxf4 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 gxf4 14. Bd2 Kh8 $1 $17 {0-1 (21) Svidler,P
(2768)-Mamedyarov,S (2804) Wijk aan Zee NED 2018}) 7... Nc6 {Once again, this
knight development is the most critical. White has several possibilities at
this point:} 8. Nd2 {This seems to be the critical move. It is very logical to
break the pin, but this will cost White a central pawn.} ({Firstly, it is
important to establish that the natural} 8. e3 $6 {would run into} g5 9. Bg3 h5
$36) ({Since 8.e3 is not possible, the alternative way of development is} 8. g3
Bf5 {with this standard developing move, Black also threatens to win an
exchange by taking on c3 with the knight and playing ...Bb4-a3. Probably, the
best move for White is} 9. Qa4 {as played in Khademalsharieh,S (2452)-Serarols
Mabras,B (2242) Caleta 2017, ½-½ (38).} ({A decent alternative is} 9. Bd2 {
Black equalized comfortably in the following game, although this is not the
only way to play with Black.} O-O 10. Bg2 Re8 11. O-O Nxd2 12. Qxd2 Ne7 13. a3
Bxc3 14. Qxc3 c6 15. Rfe1 Nc8 16. Ne5 Nd6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (46) Kavutskiy,K (2383)
-Can,E (2603) Reykjavik ISL 2018}) (9. Bg2 $6 {allows Black to carry out his
tactical idea:} Nxc3 10. bxc3 Ba3 {and the rook is trapped by the bishops.
White did not manage to get compensation for the exchange after} 11. Rb1 Bxb1
12. Qxb1 Na5 13. O-O c6 14. e4 O-O 15. exd5 cxd5 16. Ng5 g6 17. Re1 Bd6 $15 {
0-1 (18) Korley,K (2397)-Naroditsky,D (2634) Atlanta USA 2016}) (9. Qb3 {
is a different way to stop the aforementioned idea, but, as usual, it runs
into:} a5 $1 10. a3 $6 (10. a4 {was called for}) 10... a4 11. Qa2 Bxc3+ 12.
bxc3 Na5 $17 {and Black knights raided the light squares in Glud, J (2531)
-Hammer, J (2677)/Helsingor DEN 2015/0-1 (16)}) {I think that Black should not
hesitate with his queenside play and use the first opportunity to play:} 9...
a6 $5 $146 10. Bg2 b5 11. Qb3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 O-O 13. O-O h6 $11 {The last move
was played to secure the retreat for the light-squared bishop on h7. But
strategically speaking, Black has accomplished full control of light squares
c4 and e4, making White's central breaks very difficult to accomplish. In such
a position it is also difficult to make much sense of white dark-squared bishop,
despite some weaknesses on dark squares in Black's camp. Even if the position
is roughly balanced, I would prefer Black here.}) (8. h3 {looks overly
cautious and time-wasting, although it is not a bad move. One game continued:}
Bf5 9. Qa4 O-O 10. e3 a6 11. Be2 {and now in Savina,A (2343)-Cornette,D (2467)
Asnieres-sur-Seine FRA 2018, ½-½ (28), instead of the game continuation, I
would recommend} Nxc3 $5 $146 12. bxc3 Be7 13. O-O b5 14. Qb3 Na5 15. Qb2 Rb8
$132 {with very good play for Black on the queenside.}) 8... g5 $1 {A
committal move, but it is all for a good cause. White's bishop just has to be
harassed in some way as f4 is not a stable square for it. White has a choice
