1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 h6 {[#] We shift
our attention to the main move 6.Bg5. After 6...h6, White's principal response
7.Bh4 is covered in the next chapter. In this chapter, we deal with the
alternative} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 {[#] Compared to a similar position covered in the
first three chapters, the exchange on f6 is not so principled here since the
h3-c8 diagonal is open for the light-squared bishop. This makes his
development fairly simple and usually allows him to equalize without much
trouble. At this junction, the most popular continuation for White is 8.Qa4+,
which would lead to Chapter 5 by transposition, after 8...Nc6. Here, we will
take a look at all of the other notable alternatives for White. Even though
there is not too much opening theory to speak of in these lines, it is good to
study them to get a better feeling for the opening overall. The main
alternative is} 8. Qb3 ({The simplistic approach is} 8. e3 {when Black
establishes pawn structure #7 with} c6 {After} 9. Be2 ({It makes less sense to
develop the bishop to} 9. Bd3 {due to ...Bg4 at some point. For example:} O-O
10. Qc2 Bd6 11. O-O Bg4 12. Nd2 Nd7 13. Rfe1 Rfe8 14. Nf1 Nf8 15. Rab1 Re7 $15
{and Black was already ahead in his preparations for kingside attack in the
game Korley, K (2409)-Cheparinov, I (2695) Reykjavik 2016, 0-1 (29)}) 9... O-O
10. O-O {Black is very comfortable and I would rather have Black pieces in
such a position, even though it might be objectively equal. The best setup for
his pieces is: bring the knight to f6, move the queen back to e7, and bring
the bishop back to d6. As I said earlier, there is no opening theory here, so
it is better just to see some good examples to get a better feeling for the
position. Here are two:} Nd7 (10... Bd6 11. Ne1 Re8 12. Nd3 Bf5 13. Na4 Nd7 14.
Rc1 Qh4 15. g3 Qe7 $15 {1/2 (41) Brunello,S (2580)-Socko,B (2647) Legnica 2013}
) 11. a3 Bd6 12. b4 a6 13. Qb3 Qe7 14. Bd3 Nf6 {[#] Black achieved the
afore-mentioned piece setup and he is ready to start kingside offensive, which
is exactly what Black did here:} 15. Rfe1 Ne4 16. Bxe4 dxe4 17. Nd2 Be6 18. Qc2
f5 $15 {0-1 (40) Deak,S (2240)-Polgar,Z (2510) Hungary 1989}) (8. Rc1 {is less
common than 8.e3 but is actually probably a better move. The point is that
the rook on c1 x-rays the bishop on c8, which makes it difficult for Black to
keep his dark-squared bishop.} O-O ({We can see White's point in the following
variation:} 8... c6 9. a3 {and if Black insists keeping his bishop pair with}
Ba5 10. b4 Bc7 {White has} 11. Nxd5 $5 cxd5 12. Rxc7 {Truth be told, this just
leads to a draw by force after} Nc6 13. b5 Qd6 14. Rxc8+ Rxc8 15. bxc6 Rxc6 16.
Ne5 Qxa3 17. Nxc6 Qc3+ 18. Qd2 Qa1+ $11 {so if Black is happy with such
outcome, he should not fear to go for 9...Ba5.}) 9. a3 Bxc3+ {Now this
exchange is forced, but Black does not really mind.} 10. Rxc3 c6 11. e3 ({
In one of my blitz games this year, my opponent went for a less logical
fianchetto development:} 11. g3 Bf5 12. Bg2 Nd7 $11 {Black was fine and later
even better:} 13. O-O Rfe8 14. Qd2 Qd6 15. Re3 Be4 16. Bh3 $6 Nb6 $15) 11...
Bf5 {Black has no problems in the Carlsbad pawn structure. He has traded a
couple of pieces and his light-squared bishop is active. A positional battle
awaits, but it is difficult for any side to obtain initiative.} 12. Ne5 ({
A normal continuation would be} 12. Be2 Nd7 13. O-O a5 {[#] This is generally
a useful move in these positions because, in case of b2-b4, Black obtains the
