1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 {[#] In
this chapter, we will analyze White's main weapon against the Ragozin after
the 5.cxd5 exd5 exchange. White keeps the pin on the f6-knight and provokes
him into playing the weakening g7-g5 in order to unpin. Indeed, 7...g5 or 7...
c5, followed by ...g7-g5, used to be the main lines in the previous years.
However, our focus will be on a relatively fresh variation 7...0-0 8.e3 Bf5!?,
which has proved to be a reliable choice for Black lately, even on the highest
level.} O-O 8. e3 ({Rare alternatives are} 8. Qc2 c5 {which actually
transposes into our Nimzo-Indian 4.Qc2 repertoire}) ({and} 8. Qb3 {when the
principled answer is} c5 9. dxc5 Nc6 10. e3 ({In case of} 10. a3 {I like the
following pawn sacrifice:} Bxc5 $1 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Nxd5 Qe6 {and White has
trouble evacuating his knight from d5 in the variation:} 13. e3 Rd8 14. Rd1 b6
15. Be2 Bb7 $36) 10... Be6 11. Nd4 Nxd4 12. exd4 Bxc5 $1 $11) 8... Bf5 $5 {
This move is the cornerstone of our repertoire against 7.Bh4 variation. Black
would normally like to play this move, but the problem is that the b7-pawn
loses protection and it seems like this move is just bad after 9.Qb3. However,
strong engines have proven that Black obtains good compensation if he
sacrifices the b-pawn, which made this variation completely playable.
Obviously, the critical move is} 9. Qb3 {although White has many alternatives.}
({The second most popular move is} 9. Bd3 {but this is hardly a challenging
continuation. Black does not mind the exchange of light-squared bishops and
can complete his development quietly:} Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 {[#] I believe that
this move order is a tad more accurate than 10...c6, simply because we develop
a piece and keep an option of playing ...c7-c5, as well.} 11. O-O ({A more
aggressive try is} 11. Ne5 {when Black unpins with} Qe8 {and after} 12. O-O c6
13. Nxd7 Nxd7 14. a3 Bd6 15. e4 dxe4 16. Nxe4 Be7 17. Bg3 Nb6 18. Nc5 Qc8 19.
Rfe1 Nd5 $11 {[#] the position simplifies quite a bit and Black has a strong
outpost on d5. Two games were played from this position; strangely White won
