1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Qa4+ {[#] This is the third most
popular move that leads to 'pure Ragozin' positions (if we exclude more
Nimzo-like positions that arise after 5.e3, 5.g3, 5.a3, etc). Once upon a time,
this was considered as the principled way to prove that Ragozin defense is
suspicious. The reasoning was that this check forces Black to put his knight
in front of the c-pawn, which makes it more difficult for him to fight for the
center. However, a lot of water has flowed under the bridge since then, and
these days, in great part thanks to the efforts of Viacheslav Ragozin himself,
we know that Black has perfectly adequate play in this system.} Nc6 6. e3 {
White's main continuation is not too pretentious - he just wants to complete
his development as quickly as possible, using the fact that Black will need
some more time than usual to organize counterplay in the center.} (6. Ne5 {
If we exclude 6.Bg5 dxc4, that transposes to Chapter 4, and 6.cxd5 exd5, that
transposes to Chapter 5, this is White's most common alternative. He tries to
exploit the pin in a straightforward way, although playing with the queen and
a piece twice in the opening is not really the healthiest way to start the
game.} Bd7 7. Nxd7 {Like this, White wins the bishop pair.} ({The alternative
is} 7. Nxc6 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Bxc6 {Now White has a choice of queen retreats:} 9.
Qb3 {This keeps material, but also contains some risk for White.} ({Perhaps,
it is more practical for White to sacrifice a pawn for compensation with} 9.
Qc2 dxc4 10. f3 O-O (10... Nd7 $5 11. e4 Nb6 {is another reasonable plan,
preparing ...f7-f5 break at the right moment and keeping the option to castle
queenside.}) 11. e4 b5 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 Qd7 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. g4 Qd6 $15 {
with a regular extra doubled pawn for black in Hernandez Onna,R-Kozma,J
Leipzig 1975 ½-½ (48)}) ({or} 9. Qa3 dxc4 10. f3 {as in Arias,L (2253)
-Pedersen,N (2510) Havana 2006 0-1 (46), when I would prefer} b5 11. e4 Nd7 12.
Be2 a6 13. O-O f5 $1 $15 {striking at White's pawn center and clearing the
f7-square for the king, since it can not castle.}) 9... dxc4 10. Qxc4 Ne4 $1
$36 {[#] This move, endorsed by Ragozin, is surprisingly annoying for White.
The knight cannot be chased away by 11.f3, due to 11...Qh4+, winning material.
It is not so simple for him to complete development due to the weakness of
f2-square.} 11. Bf4 ({Another move seen in practice is} 11. Be3 {when Black
can simply complete development with} O-O ({or play} 11... Qh4 {transposing
into 11.Bf4.}) 12. f3 Nd6 13. Qd3 Bb5 $1 {An important part of Black's
strategic puzzle. Ragozin pioneered many ideas in this opening that we take
for granted today.} 14. Qc2 e5 $1 {Black strikes in the center at the right
time. His lead in development dictates that he plays this way.} 15. dxe5 Nc4
16. Bf4 Qh4+ 17. g3 Qh5 18. Bg2 Nxe5 19. O-O Ng6 20. Bc1 Rfe8 $15 {0-1 (45)
Freiman, S-Ragozin, V Leningrad (Russia) 1934}) ({If the engine suggests a move
like} 11. h4 $5 {as the best way to deal with ...Qh4 threat, then something
seems to be wrong with White's opening.} Qd6 12. Rh3 O-O-O $36) 11... Qf6 12.
Be3 Qh4 $1 $36 {[#] A strong move that slows down White's development and
prepares his own queenside castling.} 13. Qd3 ({White's problem is that} 13. g3
$2 {does not work due to} Nxg3 $1 14. fxg3 Qe4 $19) 13... O-O-O 14. Qc2 Nd6 15.
Qc1 f6 {with a huge lead in development, Black prepares e6-e5 break, that we
have seen in Ragozin's game as well.} 16. g3 Qh5 17. f3 e5 18. Bg2 Rhe8 19. O-O
Nc4 20. Bf2 e4 $17 {0-1 (45) Dumpor,A (2325)-Palac,M (2572) Rijeka 2001}) 7...
Nxd7 {This is a more concrete approach,} ({compared to} 7... Qxd7 {which was
played in the original game Colle-Alekhine, played almost one hundred years
ago! In that game, both players played logically until move 12:} 8. e3 e5 9. a3
exd4 10. axb4 dxc3 11. bxc3 O-O {White obtained a bishop pair against a pair
of knights, but his development has suffered a bit. Colle decided to sacrifice
a pawn for development, but that was not the best. Instead, White should play}
12. cxd5 (12. Be2 $6 dxc4 13. O-O (13. Bxc4 Qg4 $40) 13... a6 $15 {Colle,
E-Alekhine, A Hastings 1925}) 12... Qxd5 13. f3 {securing the f2-square for his
king. The position remains complex after} Rfd8 14. Be2 $13) {Black was
preparing to go 8...Nb6, so something had to give. With this move, White
releases the central tension,} 8. cxd5 ({while} 8. e3 {allows Black to nullify
White's bishop pair advantage with} Nb6 9. Qb3 Nxc4 10. Bxc4 dxc4 11. Qxc4 {
and now, the best is} Qd5 $1 {[#] forcing the queen trade and entering an
endgame that can be better only for Black.} 12. Qxd5 (12. Qxb4 $4 {is a naive
blunder:} Qxg2 $19 {0-1 (14) Stegariu,V (1942)-Sadzikowski,D (2280) Varna 2009}
) 12... Bxc3+ $1 {This is an important intermediate move that compromises
White's pawn structure (transforming from #7 to #1). This will be important to
secure a cozy outpost on c4 for Black knight.} (12... exd5 {would allow} 13.
Bd2 Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Kd7 15. Ke2 h5 $11 {1/2 (15) Khismatullin,D (2681)-Vitiugov,
N (2742) St Petersburg RUS 2014}) 13. bxc3 exd5 {[#] Once black gets his
knight to c4, it will dominate the white bishop. The a2- and c3-pawns may also
prove to be weak further down the stretch, while I don't see any potential
problems for Black in this endgame. In practice, Black had a plus score from
this position, as well. Here are some examples:} 14. Ke2 (14. f3 f5 15. Ke2
O-O-O 16. Bd2 Rhe8 17. Kd3 a6 18. Be1 Re6 19. Bg3 Rde8 20. Rae1 b5 21. Bf4 Na5
22. Re2 Nc4 $15 {0-1 (45) Laxman,R (2395)-Sadorra,J (2414) Singapore 2007}) (
14. Rb1 O-O-O 15. h4 Na5 16. g4 Rhe8 17. Ke2 Re6 18. Kd3 Rf6 $15 {1/2-1/2 (18)
Blackburn,J (2196)-Logothetis,S (2318) Liverpool 2008}) 14... Na5 15. f3 f5 16.
Bd2 O-O-O 17. Kd3 Rhe8 18. Rae1 Nc4 $15 {0-1 (63) Barbot,P (2429)-Anic,D (2381)
Drancy FRA 2016}) 8... Nb6 {This is a useful intermezzo that forces White's
response:} 9. Qb5 (9. Qb3 $4 Nxd4 $19) (9. Qd1 $2 Nxd5 10. Bd2 Nxd4 $17) {
Among several possibilities for Black, I would recommend:} 9... a6 $5 (9...
Nxd5 10. Bd2 {is more common.}) 10. Qd3 Qxd5 $1 {[#] Again, this queen move.
Basically, Black plays the Chigorin defense with a few extra tempi. This can
not be bad - White's center is already under pressure.} 11. a3 ({The
alternative is} 11. e3 {when one game continued:} f5 12. Bd2 Bxc3 13. Bxc3 ({
In case of the other capture} 13. bxc3 {Black secures his control over the
c4-square with} Na5 {and after} 14. f3 O-O 15. Be2 e5 $132 {the position is
complex, with comfortable play for Black. Knights are often better than
bishops in such positions.}) 13... O-O-O 14. Rg1 $6 {This is not a good way to
