1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 a6 5. cxd5 exd5 {[#] Pinning the knight
with 6.Bg5 is White's most popular and natural option, but he has three
notable alternatives that we will cover in this chapter. We start with} 6. Bf4
{Sometimes in Queen's gambit, the bishop is developed on this square. However,
in this case, it is not so principled since Black can offer a trade of bishops
on d6 without wasting any time.} ({If there was any dangerous alternative that
I could single out, it would have to be} 6. Qb3 {[#] With this move, White
puts pressure on both b7- and d5-pawns, while also not allowing Black to
develop his light-squared bishop, as he normally does in this opening. It was
played by several strong players and we might see its popularity increase in
the future. I could suggest two answers, one sharp and the other more
positional, so that you can choose depending on your goals.} {The sharp one is}
c5 {logically attacking White's center and keeping c5-c4 as an option to win a
tempo on the white queen.} ({A more positional option is} 6... Be7 {[#] when Black
is basically ready to play the classical exchange variation of the QGD. There
are two plusses to this approach. Firstly, Black has avoided Nge2, f3 setup
and secondly, he will most likely have an extra move ...a6 compared to the
main lines since White is likely to retreat his queen to c2 at some point.
White queen is not particularly useful on the b3-square. Clearly, such an approach can work better against players who you suspect are well
theoretically prepared, but may not be so well-versed in positional
intricacies of the Queen's gambit.} 7. Bf4 ({The other, more classical setup
is:} 7. Bg5 c6 8. e3 Nbd7 9. Bd3 ({If White plays} 9. h3 {trying to secure the
h2-retreat for his bishop, Black can answer with:} O-O 10. Bd3 Ne4 ({or} 10...
Bd6 $5 11. O-O Qc7 {with an idea similar to Chapter 13, only without the
bishop on e6.}) 11. Bf4 Ndf6 12. O-O Bd6 $13 {and White's extra h3-move gave
Black enough time to take control of e4-square and trade the dark-squared
bishops.}) 9... h6 $1 {It is important to include this move to make sure that
the h7-pawn does not hang in certain lines.} 10. Bh4 {½-½ (61) Morozov,N 
(2449)-Moiseenko,V (2554) Yerevan ARM 2018} (10. Bf4 {is not accurate since
Black can win the bishop pair with:} Nh5 $11 {as in Levin, F (2475)-Landa, K 
