1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 a6 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 {[#] This is the
main line of the Modern QGD - by far the most games in this young opening were
played from this position. As I explained in the introduction, there are pros
and cons to this variation, compared to the exchange variation of the regular
QGD. Generally speaking, Black's position is very solid and offers good
chances for a long battle where both positional and tactical strengths of a
player can be utilized. This makes it a good weapon to play for a win,
especially against specific types of opponents, as noted in the introduction.
Since the pawn structure is most likely to remain fixed as #7 for a long time 
(sometimes it transposes to #5), it is important to be well acquainted with
typical ideas and plans for both sides. The theoretical knowledge is still of
secondary importance here; what is more important is how you handle the battle
strategically. Therefore, the approach to this chapter will be a bit different
compared to the other chapters in this database. Instead of studying
variations, move by move, I have collected the most important games played so
far in this variation. I will present them in a tree of variations, as usual,
but the focus will rather be on ideas than on concrete variations. This is how
I learned to play this variation with Black and I would suggest anyone else
who would like to play it to do the same.} Be6 {As explained in the
introduction, this unusual way of defending the d5-pawn allows Black to set up
his pieces more actively than in the standard QGD. White's main continuation
now is} 7. e3 {although several alternatives exist.} ({Firstly, it is
important to understand what happens if White attacks the b7-pawn:} 7. Qb3 {
[#] Then, as we have learned previously, Black does not mind giving up the
pawn with} Nbd7 $1 {In practice, no one dared to take the pawn, admitting a
small defeat with} 8. e3 ({However, in one online blitz game, my opponent gave
me an opportunity to demonstrate Black's compensation after:} 8. Qxb7 Rb8 9.
Qxa6 Rxb2 $132 {The rook on the second rank is quite annoying for White.} 10.
a3 Qb8 ({Another good option was} 10... Be7 $5 11. e3 O-O 12. Be2 c5 $132) 11.
e3 $6 ({It was necessary to swap off the bishop first:} 11. Bxf6 Nxf6 12. e3
Rb3 $44) 11... Ne4 $36 {White is in trouble now, Black's threats are quite
serious.} 12. Qd3 $4 {A blunder.} (12. Nb5 {was the only move when after} Be7
$1 13. Bxe7 Kxe7 14. Be2 c6 $1 $36 {Black's initiative is still very strong.})
12... Rb3 $19 13. Rc1 Bxa3 14. Rc2 Bb4 {Sorin, Ariel - Kuljasevic, Davorin /
Internet Chess Club 2017, 0-1}) 8... Rb8 {Now the queen seems a bit misplaced
on b3.} 9. Qc2 ({In the other game, White kept his queen there and just
continued developing:} 9. Bd3 Bd6 10. O-O c6 11. h3 Qc7 {This is one of the
most important ideas in this opening - after h3, the white dark-squared bishop can
not retreat to the h2-b8 diagonal.} 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. Ng5 Bc8 14. f4 {White is
building up the Pillsbury attack setup.} O-O 15. Qc2 h6 16. Nf3 c5 17. Ne5 b5 {
Black's counterplay comes in time.} 18. Qf2 Bb7 19. Rac1 Qe7 20. Qh4 Rbd8 21.
Ne2 c4 $15 {and Black obtained a good version of pawn structure #4 in the game
Pultinevicius,P (2465)-Grandelius,N (2655) Batumi GEO 2018 0-1 (38)}) 9... Bd6
10. Bd3 c6 11. Bf4 {We can see that white player in this game understands
positional nuances better than the one in the previous game. This is the best
way for White to trade the dark-squared bishops.} Qc7 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. O-O h6
14. Rfc1 O-O 15. Na4 {White prepares knight transfer to c5-square.} Rfe8 16.
Nc5 {This is usually better if prepared with b4-move. Now Black can just trade
a few pieces on c5.} Nxc5 17. Qxc5 ({The pawn structure after} 17. dxc5 {
is okay for Black.} Qc7 18. b4 Bg4 $11) 17... Qxc5 18. Rxc5 Nd7 19. Rc2 a5 $11
{Black has no problems whatsoever and he eventually outplayed his grandmaster
opponent in the endgame:} 20. h3 Kf8 21. b3 Ke7 22. a3 Ra8 23. Rac1 Kd6 24. Nd2
g5 25. f3 h5 26. Kf2 h4 $15 {0-1 (67) Mirzoev,A (2510)-Rakhmanov,A (2629)
Linares ESP 2018}) ({The second similar attempt is} 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Qb3 {
[#] although I do not think that this was played in practice. After} Ra7 {
it seems quite risky to take the pawn:} 9. Nxd5 ({A safer alternative is} 9. g3
Bd6 10. Bg2 (10. Nxd5 $4 Qf5 $19) 10... O-O 11. O-O Qd8 12. Qc2 Nd7 13. Rfe1 c6
{and Black is solid.} 14. e4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Be7 $11) 9... Qd8 10. e4 c6 11. Qb6
cxd5 12. Qxa7 {White won material, but his king is exposed and Black obtains
initiative with} dxe4 ({or} 12... Bb4+ 13. Kd1 dxe4 14. Qxb7 O-O $36) 13. Nd2
Bb4 14. Qxb7 Bxd2+ 15. Kxd2 O-O $36) ({The fianchetto} 7. g3 {is a rare
possibility. It is playable, though it does not really work too well in this
structure:} Nbd7 8. Bg2 Be7 (8... Bd6 {is also playable.} 9. O-O O-O 10. Qc2 c6
11. Rad1 Qc7 12. Nh4 h6 13. Bc1 Rfe8 14. Nf5 Bf8 15. Bf4 Qc8 16. Nd6 Bxd6 17.
Bxd6 Nb6 18. Rfe1 Bf5 19. Qc1 Ne4 $11 {Black had excellent control of light
squares in Perunovic,M (2433)-Nestorovic,N (2453) Kragujevac SRB 2018 0-1 (44)}
) 9. O-O c6 10. Qc2 O-O 11. Rad1 Re8 $11 {Black is fully mobilized and White
should have probably just accepted that the position is equal. However, as it
usually happens with players who do not fully understand this type of position,
White continued to play too aggressively with} 12. Ne5 $6 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Ng4 14.
Bxe7 Qxe7 15. e4 dxe4 16. Qxe4 Qc5 $15 {and Black had an advantage thanks to
