to seek counterplay on the queenside than ...b7-b5.} 19. b4 Nce4 20. Qb2 Nxc3
21. Rxc3 Rxc3 22. Qxc3 Rc8 23. Qa1 Qc7 $11 {The position is roughly equal, but
Carlsen demonstrated once again how he can get a full point out of such
positions:} 24. Nd4 Qc3 25. Bc2 Ne4 26. Bxe4 dxe4 27. Qxc3 Rxc3 28. Ra1 Kf8 29.
Kf1 Ke7 30. Ke1 Kd6 $15 {0-1 Riazantsev,A (2671)-Carlsen,M (2840)/Doha QAT
2016/The Week in Chess 1156 (62)}) ({White could fight against the c7-c5 break
with} 12. Rac1 c6 13. Na4 {After} Rfe8 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Nc5 (15. b4 Bg4 16.
Nd2 b6 $1 $13) 15... Nxc5 16. Qxc5 Qxc5 17. dxc5 a5 $1 $11 {Black had equal
chances in the endgame and eventually outplayed his opponent:} 18. a4 g6 19.
Nd4 Kg7 20. f3 Bd7 21. Kf2 Nh7 22. g4 Ng5 23. h4 Ne6 $11 {0-1 (58) Nesterov,A 
(2355)-Khanin, S (2494) Yekaterinburg RUS 2018}) 12... Rac8 $5 {[#] This is
pretty much the most principled continuation of Black's previous play because
he has saved a tempo on c7-c5 break by not having to play c7-c6 earlier. This
will lead to an isolated queen's pawn position where Black is very well
centralized and White can hardly do anything with his theoretical positional
advantage. Arguably, this approach takes away some mystery from the position
and may lead to further simplifications. If you feel that you need to keep the
structure more complex, than playing ...c7-c6 instead of ...c7-c5 would be the
right choice. Still, it is useful to have this kind of position in the arsenal,
as well.} ({A similar approach, only with a different rook was seen in the
game:} 12... Rfc8 13. Rfd1 c5 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. dxc5 Rxc5 16. Qa4 Ne5 17. Nxe5
Qxe5 18. Ne2 Qxb2 19. Rab1 Bd7 20. Qxa6 Qxa2 21. Qxa2 Rxa2 22. Rxb7 g6 $11 {
1/2-1/2 (40) Xu,Y (2533)-Aravindh,C (2579) Bhubaneswar IND 2018}) 13. Rac1 (13.
Ne5 {trades an extra pair of pieces, but this is not the kind of exchange that
bothers Black too much. After} c5 14. Nxd7 Nxd7 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. dxc5 Rxc5 17.
Rfd1 Rfc8 18. Be2 Qc7 19. Rd4 Ne5 $132 {he obtained active piece play in
Cvetkovic,N (2278)-Harsha,B (2465) Paracin SRB 2018 0-1 (33)}) 13... c5 14.
Bxd6 Qxd6 15. dxc5 Nxc5 {Black looks for quick counterplay via e4-square. It
is not so easy for White to regroup as he would like to. Russian GM Vadim
Zvjaginsev played this variation with success twice.} 16. Rfd1 Qb6 17. Nd4 (17.
Qe2 Nce4 ({Another way to equalize was} 17... d4 $5 18. Nxd4 Nxd3 19. Qxd3 Qxb2
$11) 18. Nd4 Nxc3 19. bxc3 {1/2-1/2 (19) Potkin,V (2574)-Zvjaginsev,V (2629)
Tula RUS 2018}) 17... Nce4 18. Bxe4 {Here, I think that the a better way to
equalize is} Nxe4 $5 $146 {threatening to take on c3, transposing into a pawn
structure #2 with a backward c3-pawn.} (18... dxe4 19. Nxe6 ({White could keep
some positonal pressure with} 19. a3 $14) 19... Qxe6 20. Rd4 Rc5 21. Qb3 Qxb3
22. axb3 Re8 23. b4 Rc6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (34) Zhou Jianchao (2625)-Zvjaginsev,V 
(2644) Xingtai CHN 2018}) {In case of} 19. Nde2 Nxc3 20. Nxc3 {Black would have
} d4 $1 21. Rxd4 Bxa2 $11 *

