1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Bg5 {[#] This sideline is quite reasonable -
White develops his dark-squared bishop naturally, hoping to get into a normal
middlegame without having to worry about heaps of opening theory after 4.Nc3.
Since our repertoire is based on the Ragozin defense, I suggest the following
response:} Bb4+ {Now, White can defend against the check with either 5.Nc3,
which leads into the 5.Bg5 variation of the Ragozin by transposition, or he
can play} 5. Nbd2 $5 {[#] This is an interesting way to avoid the mainstream
Ragozin theory. However, the knight is not placed so actively on d2, as it is
on c3, so Black's principled continuation is:} dxc4 {With his knight on d2, 6.
e4 just does not make much sense. Black can defend the pawn with 6...b5 7.a4
c6 and White cannot make use of his pawn center. Therefore, White resorts to
other ways to prove his compensation:} 6. Qc2 {This is the most flexible
continuation. White attacks the c4-pawn, keeping both e2-e3 and g2-g3
developing options open.} (6. e3 {is another reasonable approach. Black will,
of course, protect the pawn with} b5 {and now White usually tries to undermine
the c4-pawn with b2-b3, hoping to obtain a positional compensation due to the
pressure along the semi-open files on the queenside.} 7. Be2 ({I think that it
is less accurate to start with} 7. a4 c6 8. Qc2 Bb7 9. Be2 Nbd7 10. O-O O-O 11.
b3 {It is hard to suggest anything better for White.} ({For example,} 11. Ne4
$6 h6 12. Bh4 Be7 $15 {hardly offers him the compensation he is looking for.})
11... c3 $1 {Black's main idea is to push c6-c5, so he should keep White busy
in the meantime and avoid opening of files on the queenside.} ({In that sense,
} 11... cxb3 {would offer White compensation after:} 12. Nxb3 Rc8 13. Qb2 a5
14. Ne5 $44) 12. Ne4 bxa4 $1 {This is the most efficient way to prepare the ...
c6-c5 break.} 13. Rxa4 a5 14. Nxc3 c5 $15 {[#] and Black already had the upper
hand in Barbot, P (2422)-Kuljasevic, D (2538) Karlsruhe GER 2018 ½-½ (51).
White continued poorly in the game, but even after the relatively best:} 15.
Na2 Nb6 16. Nxb4 cxb4 17. Raa1 Qc8 $15 {Black's chances are better due to the
queenside majority and control of the central squares.}) 7... Bb7 8. O-O O-O 9.
b3 (9. a4 $2 {is just pointless. Black was clearly better after:} a6 10. axb5
axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 $17 12. b3 c3 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Nb1 c5 $19 {0-1 (48)
Joppien,A (2107)-Landa,K (2639)/Senden 2011/EXT 2012}) {Here, I would suggest
a similar approach as in 7.a4 variation above:} 9... c3 $5 $146 (9... Bxd2 {
was not so convincing for Black in the following game:} 10. Qxd2 cxb3 11. axb3
a6 12. Rfc1 Nbd7 13. Qe1 Bd5 14. Nd2 Qb8 15. f3 $14 {0-1 (32) Penttinen,J 
(2322)-Moiseenko,A (2678)/Kallithea 2008/CBM 127}) 10. a3 ({or} 10. Nb1 c5 11.
a3 Ba5 $13) 10... Be7 11. Nb1 c5 12. Nxc3 a6 $11 {and Black is completely fine.
}) (6. Qa4+ {is a move that forces} Nc6 {and prevents 7...b5. However, after}
7. e3 ({or} 7. a3 Bxd2+ 8. Bxd2 Qd5 $1 {with the similar idea as in the main
line.} 9. Qc2 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Bc3 {Now} Qc5 $146 {would secure Black's
advantage because White can not compensate for both missing pawns.} (11... Qg4
{was less clear-cut:} 12. f3 Qh4+ 13. g3 Qh6 14. e4 Bd7 15. Bxc4 Bc6 16. Qf2
O-O 17. O-O $44 {1-0 Carlsen,M (2775)-Morozevich,A (2788)/Moscow 2008}) 12. e3
Bd7 13. Bb4 Qc6 $15) {Black has an important resource in} 7... Qd5 {[#] when
the c4-pawn is protected, while Black is simultaneously ready to push ...b7-b5.
After} 8. Bxf6 b5 9. Qc2 gxf6 10. a4 {as in the game Sinadinovic,A (2000)
-Barle,J (2420)/Caorle 1989/0-1, Black has a strong improvement:} Na5 $1 $146
11. axb5 Bd7 {winning the b5-pawn, at least.} 12. Be2 (12. e4 Qb7 $15) 12...
Nb3 $15) (6. a3 {is a fairly new and interesting approach. White is not too
concerned with returning the pawn, but he rather wants to secure the bishop
pair advantage and play for a long-term compensation.} Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 {Here,
instead of the standard 7...b5, I suggest a rare, but logical alternative:} O-O
$5 {[#] Black does not insist on protecting his extra-pawn and focuses on
completion of his development instead.} ({A more popular approach is the
materialistic:} 7... b5 8. a4 c6 9. g3 Bb7 10. Bg2 Nbd7 11. Ne5 $44 {when,
having gotten rid of the poorly placed d2-knight, White has decent
compensation. In the following grandmaster game, he obtained good attacking
prospects after:} Qc8 12. O-O O-O 13. e4 a6 14. f4 c5 15. d5 $36 {1-0 (28)
Ipatov,A (2648)-Brkic,A (2584) Gjakova 2016}) 8. a4 {This move was seen in
Dondukov,S (2279)-Gundavaa,B (2493) Ulan Ude 2011 ½-½ (89). White wants to
make sure that Black does not play ...b7-b5. However, it is also a waste of
time in the opening.} ({Alternatives are:} 8. e3 b5 {Now that White has
committed with e2-e3 and the fianchetto is not in his plans, Black does not
mind playing this move.} 9. a4 c6 10. Be2 Nbd7 11. O-O Bb7 12. Rfd1 $44 {
White has some compensation, but Black has nothing to complain about either.})
({and} 8. g3 {when Black can simply continue in the Nimzo-Indian spirit with:}
b6 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Qxc4 Nbd7 11. Bg2 c5 12. O-O Bd5 $11) 8... h6 9. Bh4 {
and I believe that Black should use his lead in development with vigorous play
in the center:} c5 $1 10. dxc5 Na6 $132) ({There are two more alternatives
worth mentioning:} 6. Rc1 b5 7. g3 Bb7 8. Bg2 Nbd7 9. O-O c5 10. a3 Bxd2 11.
Bxd2 O-O 12. b3 cxd4 13. bxc4 bxc4 14. Bb4 Re8 15. Qxd4 Nb6 $15 {1-0 Maljutin,
E-Lopushnoy,D/Moscow 1996/EXT 2000 (44)}) ({and} 6. g3 b5 7. a4 {as in the
game Kunte,A (2513)-Smerdon,D (2489) Canberra 2009 ½-½ (30), when I would
prefer the classical approach:} c6 8. Bg2 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Ne5 Qc8 {and
White still has to prove his compensation.}) 6... b5 7. a4 c6 8. g3 {In
general, White's strongest setup against c6-b5 pawn chain is the one with his
bishop on g2.} ({White can also include the exchange on f6} 8. Bxf6 {, when it
is important to remember to take back with the pawn:} gxf6 {[#] This pawn
structure is fine for Black. The f6-pawn prevents Nf3-e5 jump in some
variations.} ({since} 8... Qxf6 $6 {runs into:} 9. axb5 cxb5 10. Qe4 $18 {
and there is no way to avoid huge material losses. The difference is that
after 8...gxf6, 10.Qe4 could be answered with 10...Qd5.}) 9. g3 Bb7 10. Bg2 a5
11. O-O Nd7 12. b3 cxb3 13. Nxb3 bxa4 14. Rxa4 Ba6 $1 {Rapport made sure to
control the ...c6-c5 break, but Wojtaszek found an alternative plan to
activate his light-squared bishop:} 15. Ra2 Bb5 $15 {and White had no
compensation for the pawn and Black's strong bishop pair.} 16. Rfa1 O-O 17. Nc1
Rc8 18. Nd3 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 c5 $17 {0-1 (34) Rapport,R (2671)-Wojtaszek,R (2733)/
Biel 2015/CBM 168/[Pavlovic, M]}) ({As I mentioned earlier, White is not really
placed well for} 8. e4 {After} h6 9. Bxf6 (9. Bh4 $6 {does not work because of}
g5 10. Bg3 g4 11. Ne5 Qxd4 $17) 9... Qxf6 10. Be2 ({The attempt to undermine
the pawn chain while the king is still on e8, with:} 10. axb5 $2 cxb5 11. b3 {
fails to} Nc6 $1 12. bxc4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Rd1 Bb7 $19 {0-1 Saljova,
S-Botsari Miladinovic,A/Hradec Kralove 1992/TD (25)}) 10... O-O 11. O-O Nd7 12.
b3 {and now, the standard:} c3 $1 {[#] gives Black the edge.} 13. e5 Qe7 14.
Ne4 bxa4 15. Rxa4 a5 16. Nxc3 Bb7 17. Ne4 c5 $17 {0-1 Sandipan,C-Morozevich,A/
Dresden 2008/CBM 128 (34)}) 8... Bb7 9. Bg2 Nbd7 10. O-O O-O {[#] After
logical developing moves from both sides, we reached an important position.
White has two basic ways to prove his compensation:} {1)} 11. b3 ({and 2)} 11.
Ne5 Qc8 {Black unpins and simultaneously defends the b7-bishop. The next thing
on his agenda is the ...c6-c5 break.} 12. b3 (12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. Ne4 Be7 {
This retreat is important in order to prepare the ...c6-c5 break.} 14. b3 c5 $1
15. bxc4 b4 $15) 12... c5 $1 {[#] A very strong move. Black returns the extra
pawn, but activates his pieces and remains with a superior pawn structure:} 13.
Bxb7 Qxb7 14. bxc4 Bxd2 15. Bxd2 b4 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. dxc5 a5 $15 {0-1
Krasenkow,M (2640)-Gajewski,G (2629)/Warsaw 2014/CBM 160 (29)}) 11... c3 $5
$146 {[#] You may have noticed that this is the preferred way to meet White's
b2-b3 in this type of position.} ({The alternative:} 11... cxb3 {is also
playable, but I believe that White has good compensation after:} 12. Nxb3 a5
13. Ne5 $44 Qb6 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Rfc1 Rfc8 16. Nc5 Nd5 17. e3 $6 (17. Be4 $44)
17... Bxc5 18. Qxc5 b4 $15 {0-1 Bogner,S (2570)-Georgiadis,N (2441)/
Switzerland 2014/EXT 2015 (42)}) {We get a sharp tactical fight after:} 12. Ne4
c5 $1 13. Ne5 ({In case of} 13. Nd6 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 {Black is happy to sacrifice
the exchange with:} cxd4 $1 15. Bxa8 Qxa8 16. Nxb5 e5 $17 {since his strong
central pawn chain more than compensates for it.}) 13... cxd4 $5 {With this
double-edged move, Black can try to obtain the initiative.} ({A calmer
alternative is} 13... Qc7 14. Nxf6+ Nxf6 15. Bxb7 Qxb7 16. dxc5 Qd5 17. Bxf6
gxf6 18. Nd3 Bxc5 19. b4 (19. axb5 Rac8 $15) 19... Bd4 20. e3 Be5 21. axb5 Rfd8
22. Nxe5 Qxe5 23. Ra3 Rac8 24. Rc1 $11) 14. Nxf6+ (14. Nxd7 Bxe4 15. Nxf6+ gxf6
16. Bxe4 fxg5 17. Bxa8 Qxa8 $15 {and Black's pawn-chain is a strong long-term
asset.}) 14... gxf6 15. Bxf6 $1 Nxf6 16. Bxb7 Rb8 $13 {with an interesting
fight ahead.} *

