1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. e3 b6 {[#] As I mentioned in the introduction,
among several good responses to White's positional setup, I would like to
suggest this Queen's-Indian approach. Black plans to develop his bishops to b7
and d6 and the knight on d7. This usually leads to complex middlegames with
lots of possibilities for both sides, which is something that White is,
presumably, playing for when he chooses 4.e3. The downside for White is that
Black gets easy and natural development and is usually not under any pressure
in the opening. White has several positional setups in this variation. The
most common one is:} 5. Nc3 ({After} 5. b3 Bb7 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O {he has
two alternative setups:} {1)} 8. cxd5 ({and 2)} 8. Bb2 Nbd7 9. Nbd2 ({The
Pillsbury attack:} 9. Ne5 {does not work so well here, because after} c5 10.
Nd2 {Black can clear the center with pawn exchanges:} cxd4 11. exd4 dxc4 12.
Ndxc4 Be7 $11 {and it is difficult to speak of any significant attack for
White here. For example:} 13. Re1 Rc8 14. Re3 b5 15. Nd2 a6 16. Rh3 g6 $15 {
0-1 (63) Littlewood,P (2368)-Georgiev,K (2654) Coventry 2005}) 9... c5 {
In this symmetrical position, White can try to use his first-move advantage to
achieve a desired middlegame structure: either the hanging pawns after} 10. Rc1
({or the Pillsbury attack with:} 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Ne5 Qe7 12. f4 cxd4 13. exd4
Ne4 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Bc4 Nf6 16. Qe2 Ba3 $11 {0-1 (80) Kulakov,V (2380)
-Bogner,S (2504) Kemer 2009}) 10... Qe7 11. cxd5 exd5 12. dxc5 bxc5 {[#]
Caruana showed that Black can rely on his piece play in the following game:}
13. Re1 Rfe8 14. Nf1 Rad8 15. Ng3 g6 16. Bb5 a6 17. Ba4 Ne4 18. Nxe4 dxe4 19.
Nd2 Ne5 $1 $132 {1/2-1/2 (76) Nakamura,H (2785)-Caruana,F (2808) Paris 2017})
8... exd5 9. Ba3 $5 {This idea has gained in popularity recently. White
postpones development of the b1-knight in order to offer this bishops exchange.
Black is not too keen to trade his active dark-squared bishop for the usually
passive white counterpart. Therefore, he should avoid the exchange with:} c5 {
and after} 10. Nc3 Nbd7 {[#] we get an interesting middlegame. White's idea
was to provoke ...c7-c5 so that he can open the position by taking on c5 at
the right moment. He will probably need to lose a tempo by retreating his
bishop to b2 at some point, but that is not such a big issue. The arising
middlegame gives chances to both sides.} 11. Rc1 ({Radjabov showed some
important ideas for Black in the following game:} 11. Nb5 Be7 12. Rc1 Re8 13.
Re1 a6 14. Nc3 Ne4 15. Ne2 Ndf6 16. Ne5 Bf8 17. f3 c4 $1 18. Bxf8 cxd3 19. Qxd3
Rxf8 20. fxe4 Nxe4 $15 {0-1 (49) Hamitevici,V (2519)-Radjabov,T (2741)
Hersonissos GRE 2017}) 11... Re8 (11... g6 $5 {is an interesting alternative
that does weaken the a1-h8 diagonal but also prevents Bd3-f5. Black equalized
without any issues in the following game:} 12. Qe2 Re8 13. Ba6 {White's idea
is to weaken the d5-pawn by trading the light-squared bishops. However, Black
has a forced way to simplify the situation in the center:} Bxa6 14. Qxa6 cxd4
$1 15. exd4 (15. Nxd4 Nc5 16. Qe2 Nxb3 $1 $15 {is the tactical point.}) 15...
Bf4 16. Rce1 Qc7 17. Qd3 a6 18. g3 Bh6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (32) Mons,L (2500)
-Rodshtein,M (2699) Munich GER 2018}) 12. Bf5 {This is the best continuation
for White. In some instances, the bishop can be traded for d7-knight in order
to target the hanging pawns. Otherwise, it can be maneuvered slowly toward the
g2-square (Bf5-h3, g2-g3, Bh3-g2), from where it would exert pressure
against the black center.} ({The other side of the board is not so comfortable for
the bishop:} 12. Bb5 $6 Rc8 13. Bb2 a6 {and now White should have just
retreated, but he made a positional mistake with:} 14. Bxd7 $2 Qxd7 15. Na4 Qd8
$15 {0-1 (28) Lorparizangeneh,S (2493)-Sethuraman,S (2657) Hamedan IRI 2018})
12... Rc8 $146 {This move is more accurate} ({than} 12... Bf8 {because this
allowed White to force the position with IQP, with:} 13. dxc5 $1 {and now
Black is forced to take on c5 with the piece:} Nxc5 ({since} 13... bxc5 {
loses one of the central pawns after} 14. Bxd7 Qxd7 15. Na4) 14. Bb2 g6 {
and now in the game Dominguez Perez, L (2739)-So, W (2788) Saint Louis USA 2017
0-1 (55), White could have obtained a slightly more pleasant position after}
15. Bb1) 13. Re1 ({Now} 13. dxc5 {can be met with} bxc5 {and the c8-rook
protects the c5-pawn. Meanwhile, Black does not have to be too concerned about
the pin on the knight. He can always unpin with ...Rc8-c7.}) 13... g6 14. Bh3
Bf8 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Bb2 Rc7 $13 {and we get a complex position with mutual
chances.}) 5... Bd6 $5 {This move order is a bit more accurate than immediate 5..
.Bb7, because it allows Black to remain more flexible with his light-squared
bishop.} 6. b3 {This is by far the most common setup for White.} ({The
following typical idea:} 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5+ {works much better for White
with black bishop already on b7. In this case, after} c6 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Re8
$11 {White is denied the e3-e4 option, which would be possible in 5...Bb7
variation.} 10. Re1 Ne4 11. Ne2 f5 12. Qc2 Bb7 13. Rb1 Nd7 $15 {1-0 (49)
Gajewski,G (2601)-Bosiocic,M (2624) Katowice POL 2017}) ({Another interesting
idea is} 6. Qc2 O-O 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nb5 {but it can be met well with:} Bb4+ 9.
Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Nxd2 a6 $1 {Taking on c7 is out of question, so the knight has
to retreat:} 11. Nc3 (11. Nxc7 $4 Ra7 $19) {and after} 11... c5 {Black already
takes over the initiative:} 12. Be2 cxd4 13. exd4 Nc6 14. Nf3 Bg4 15. Rd1 Re8
16. O-O Qd6 17. a3 b5 18. h3 Bh5 $15 {0-1 (91) Lintchevski,D (2563)-Howell,D 
(2685) Tallinn 2016}) 6... Bb7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bb2 a6 {[#] Against
White's slow setup, Black used the opportunity to develop his dark-squared
bishop more actively than usual (on d6 instead of e7). This kind of position
leads to a complex middlegame with a lot of options for both sides. We will
take a look at some key games here to get acquainted with typical ideas and
plans for both sides.} 10. Rc1 {This is the most common move.} (10. Qe2 {
prepares e3-e4, so it should be met with} Ne4 {[#] Black can fortify the
knight with ...f7-f5 and even prepare a kingside attack later. His position is
quite comfortable, as the following games suggest:} 11. Rfd1 (11. a4 {is also
possible, with a similar idea as in 10.a4. After} a5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Nb5 Bb4
14. Qc2 c6 15. Nc3 f5 {Black is very solid.} 16. Ne2 Qe7 17. Ne5 Nxe5 18. dxe5
g6 19. Nf4 Nc5 20. Be2 Ne6 $11 {0-1 (43) Sargissian,G (2672)-Riazantsev,A 
(2650) Riyadh KSA 2017}) 11... Qe7 12. Rac1 f5 13. Na4 {0-1 (51) Ivanov,S 
(2551)-Anisimov,P (2503) St Petersburg 2009} (13. h3 {1-0 (69) Bacrot,E (2695)
-Cornette,M (2586) chess.com INT 2017} {could have been answered also with}
dxc4 $1 $146 14. bxc4 Rf6 {and Black starts the kingside attack. If White
closes down the long diagonal with} 15. d5 {he surrenders the c5-square:} Ndc5
$15) 13... dxc4 $5 $146 {[#] This exchange often works very well for Black in
this variation. The fact that it allows White to strengthen his pawn center is
less important than the opportunity for Black to use his light-squared bishop
in the attack.} 14. bxc4 Rad8 15. Nc3 Qf6 $132) (10. a4 {has been a relatively
recent try to destabilize Black's queenside. I believe that the best response
is:} c5 11. cxd5 exd5 $13 {[#] when we reach pawn structure #10. However, due
to White's 10th move, the b3-pawn and b4-square have been weakened, which
should be a positional plus for Black. The ensuing middlegame gives chances to
both sides. Here are a few examples:} 12. Qe2 (12. Rc1 Qe7 13. Re1 Rfd8 14. Bf1
Nf8 {I like this knight maneuver to e6 in various hanging pawns structures.
The knight is much more actively placed on e6 than d7.} 15. g3 Ne6 16. Bg2 Rac8
17. Re2 Bc6 18. Rd2 Qb7 19. h4 Qb8 20. Ne5 Bb7 21. Nf3 h6 22. Ne2 c4 $132 {
1/2-1/2 (32) Leko,P (2679)-Kraemer,M (2575) Deizisau GER 2018}) 12... Re8 13.
Rfd1 Qe7 (13... Nf8 $5 {is possible here, too.}) 14. Rac1 Ne4 (14... g6 15. h3
cxd4 16. Nxd4 Nc5 17. Bc2 Rac8 18. Qe1 Nfe4 $13 {0-1 (63) Anton Guijarro,D 
(2650)-Lalith,B (2587) Doha QAT 2016}) 15. Bb1 Rad8 16. h3 Ndf6 17. a5 bxa5 18.
Na4 cxd4 19. Bxd4 Ba3 $13 {1-0 (43) Anton Guijarro,D (2650)-Zhigalko,S (2671)
Tallinn EST 2016}) ({White can also release the central tension at once:} 10.
cxd5 exd5 {We will reach a similar position in the main line of 10.Rc1.} 11.
Ne2 Qe7 12. Ng3 g6 13. Qe2 Ne4 14. Rfc1 h5 $5 {[#] In this typical position, I
prefer this move to ...f7-f5, because it does not weaken king's residence so
much and because we can often push the pawn all the way to h3, creating some
weaknesses around white king.} 15. Rc2 h4 16. Nf1 h3 17. g3 c5 18. Rac1 a5 $5
19. Bb5 Qe6 $13 {0-1 (37) Piasetski,L (2327)-Matlakov,M (2701)/Caleta ENG 2017/
The Week in Chess 1160}) (10. Qc2 {is similar to 10.Qe2 as far as preparing
e3-e4 goes, but it also leaves the kingside somewhat exposed, so it is far
from an ideal choice for White.} dxc4 11. bxc4 c5 $5 $146 {[#] This new move
keeps the tension in the position.} ({If he wants, Black can pretty much force
a draw with:} 11... Bxf3 12. gxf3 Nd5 $5 13. cxd5 Qg5+ 14. Kh1 Qh5 15. f4 Qf3+
16. Kg1 Qg4+ $11 {1/2-1/2 (20) Foisor,S (2258)-Paikidze,N (2346) Saint Louis
2016}) {Some possible variations are:} 12. d5 (12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Bxe4 14.
Qxe4 cxd4 15. Qxd4 Nf6 $11) (12. Rad1 cxd4 13. exd4 $2 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Nh5 $17)
12... exd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. cxd5 b5 15. a4 c4 $132) ({The last option to
prepare e3-e4 is} 10. Re1 {when Black responds similarly as to 10.Qe2:} Ne4 11.
a3 f5 12. b4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Qe7 $13 {and Black has a nice outpost on e4, active
bishops and potential for kingside attack. What more does one need with Black
out of the opening?} 14. Nxe4 $6 fxe4 15. Ne5 Bxe5 16. dxe5 Rf5 $36 {0-1 (27)
Timofeev,A (2583)-Khismatullin,D (2627) Yaroslavl RUS 2018}) 10... Qe7 {
This is one of the perks of developing the bishop to d6 - the queen can be
placed comfortably on e7, connecting the rooks. White has several ways to
continue now:} 11. cxd5 (11. Na4 {[#] This is a fairly typical move for this
variation. White prepares Nf3-e5. Black, again, has a good answer in:} dxc4 $1
12. bxc4 c5 {opening up both his bishops and establishing a fluid pawn
structure in the center.} 13. Qe2 (13. Ne5 Rad8 14. f4 cxd4 15. exd4 Ba3 $13 {
0-1 (59) Franco Ocampos,Z (2507)-Delgado Ramirez,N (2609) Asuncion PAR 2015})
13... cxd4 14. exd4 Ba3 15. Ne5 Bxb2 16. Qxb2 Rab8 $11 {1/2 (50) Dizdar,G 
(2510)-Dizdarevic,E (2465) Pula 1995}) (11. Re1 {leads to a nice version of
the hanging pawns for Black after:} Ne4 12. Qc2 f5 13. Ne2 c5 14. cxd5 exd5 15.
dxc5 bxc5 $15 {[#] and Black dominated in the following encounter:} 16. Ng3 a5
17. Red1 Rf7 18. Bb5 Rd8 19. Ba1 Nf8 20. Nh5 Ng6 $17 {preparing ...f5-f4 with
a strong attack in Fedorovsky,M (2498)-Adams,M (2745) Munich GER 2016 0-1 (41)}
) (11. Qe2 Ne4 12. Rc2 f5 13. Rfc1 Rf6 14. g3 Rh6 15. Na4 dxc4 $1 16. bxc4 c5
$36 {was another example of succesful black strategy in Shengelia,D (2557)
-Gajewski,G (2621) Czech Republic CZE 2017 ½-½ (37)}) 11... exd5 12. Ne2 (12.
Bf5 g6 13. Bh3 Ne4 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Nd2 {and now, in the game Reeh, O (2442)
-Adams, M (2682) Heidelberg GER 2010 1/2 (74), very strong would have been:} b5
$1 $15 {preparing the transfer of the knight to b6 and d5.}) 12... Ne4 13. Qc2
Rac8 {Otherwise, White could go 14.Ne5!} 14. Ng3 g6 15. Qe2 {White provoked
the rook to c8 so that he can attack the a6-pawn, but it turns out that Black
does not need to defend it.} Rfe8 ({Also possible is} 15... h5 {when White
decided to bail with:} 16. Ne5 $5 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Bxe5 18. Bxe5 Qxe5 19. Nxe4
dxe4 20. Bxa6 Bxa6 21. Qxa6 Ra8 22. Qe2 $11 {1/2-1/2 (57) Harikrishna,P (2732)
-Navara,D (2727) Prague CZE 2018}) 16. Rc2 h5 $5 {[#] as I explained earlier,
this is the preferred way to attack on the kingside.} 17. Rfc1 h4 18. Nf1 h3
19. g3 b5 20. a4 bxa4 21. bxa4 {Unfortunately, the game Gelashvili, T (2614)
-Adams, M (2697) Konya TUR 2010 0-1 (21) does not have any more moves in the
database, although it is clear that after, for example:} c5 $15 {Black has the
upper hand in this complex position.} *

